DATA EXPLORATION

MA PLOT

Alpha threshold to pick ? Rather alpha = 0.1 (default). Points will be colored blue if the adjusted p value is less than alpha. Points which fall out of the window are plotted as open triangles pointing either up or down.

plotMA(res, alpha = 0.05, main = "MA Plot: Control vs Disease")

Interpretation: A horizontal spread of points around the zero line indicates a balanced comparison, while a skewed spread might suggest biases

High abs(LFC) for a lot of low count data.

Shrinkage

Shrinkage might be useful (shrunken fold changes are useful for ranking genes by effect size and for visualization). > The shrunken log fold changes are useful for ranking and visualization, without the need for arbitrary filters on low count genes.

DESEQ2-Tutorial

resNorm <- lfcShrink(dds, coef=2, type="normal")
resLFC <- lfcShrink(dds, coef=2, type="apeglm")
resAsh <- lfcShrink(dds, coef=2, type="ashr")

MA Plots after shrinkage:

par(mfrow=c(2,2), mar=c(3,3,2,1))
xlim <- c(1, 1e5); ylim <- c(-2, 2)
plotMA(res, xlim=xlim,  main="Before Shrinkage")
plotMA(resLFC, xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, main="apeglm") # load library(apeglm) to work
plotMA(resNorm, xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, main="normal")
plotMA(resAsh, xlim=xlim, ylim=ylim, main="ashr")
mtext("MA Plots Comparison", outer = TRUE, cex = 0.9, line = -1, side = 2)

Well prefer apeglm and use resLFC for visualization purposes of DEGs in plots like Heatmaps, VolcanoPlots etc.

When use shrinken values?

For example, if you wanted to subset your significant genes based on fold change for further evaluation, you may want to use shruken values.

VST

In RNA-Seq data variance grows with the mean.

This function calculates a variance stabilizing transformation (VST) from the fitted dispersion-mean relation(s) and then transforms the count data (normalized by division by the size factors or normalization factors), yielding a matrix of values which are now approximately homoskedastic (having constant variance along the range of mean values). The transformation also normalizes with respect to library size. The rlog is less sensitive to size factors, which can be an issue when size factors vary widely. These transformations are useful when checking for outliers or as input for machine learning techniques such as clustering or linear discriminant analysis. source

Apply Variance stabilizing transformation (useful for clustering or when used as input in machine learning algoritgmis, data should be homoskedastic):

vsd <- vst(dds, blind=FALSE)
meanSdPlot(assay(vsd))

## save vsd as rds object to later use input for further analysis like WGCNA 
## we later excluded the WGCNA 
saveRDS(object = vsd, file = paste0(dir, "ANALYSIS/DEGs/Output/vsd.rds"))

PCA

PCA can be used to visualize variation between expression analysis samples. This method is especially useful for quality control, for example in identifying problems with your experimental design, mislabeled samples, or other problems. PCA

Use vst transformed data for pca as recommended in Deseq2 Tutorial.

PCA Plot without differentiating between replicates:

pcadata <- plotPCA(vsd, intgroup= c("Group", "Replicate"), returnData = T) #using the DESEQ2 plotPCA
pcadata
plotPCA(vsd, intgroup="Group")

Using ggplot2:

percentVar <- round(100 * attr(pcadata, "percentVar"))

pca_plot <-ggplot(pcadata, aes(PC1, PC2, color = Group)) +
  geom_point(size = 4) +
  ggtitle("PCA Plot (RNAseq)") +
  # theme_bw() +
  theme_gray() +

DEGS

Differentially expressed genes:

After exploring our data and obtaining initial insights, we now aim to identify significant genes. By setting specific thresholds, we can extract these from our results. Well consider genes as significant if they have a log2 fold change (LFC) greater than 0.5 and a p-value less than alpha.

Genes with a positive log2 fold change will be classified as upregulated, while those with a negative log2 fold change will be classified as downregulated (so we filtered only based on padj initially).

lfc_cutoff = 0.5
alpha = 0.05
sig_005 <- resShrink %>% as.data.frame() %>% 
  mutate(gene_exp = ifelse(log2FoldChange < 0, "down", "up")) %>% 
  dplyr::filter(padj < alpha) #  & abs(log2FoldChange < 0.5) 

sig_005

Boxplot

Boxplot of control vs disease (count distribution across samples):

counts <-counts(dds) %>% 
  as.data.frame() %>% 
  rownames_to_column(var = "ENSEMBL_ID")

counts_melt <- reshape2::melt(counts, 
                  variable.name = "Name", 
                  value.name = "Count")

counts_merge <- merge(counts_melt, 
                          sample_data, by = "Name") %>% arrange(Group)

counts_merge <- counts_merge %>%
  mutate(Name = factor(Name, levels = unique(Name[order(Group)])))


boxplot_rep_all <- ggplot(counts_merge, 
                     aes(x = reorder(Name, Group), 
                         y = log(Count), 
                         color = Group)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  geom_point(aes(color  = Group))+
  labs(title = "Distribution of Counts (disease vs control)",
       x = "Sample",
       y = "Log_Count") + 
  theme_gray()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(face = "bold", 
                                   size = 10, angle = 90, hjust = 1)) +
  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(face = "bold", size =10))
